instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The digital‑twin architecture follows a service‑oriented pattern where the six containers are coordinated via an MQTT broker for event‑driven signalling and a common TimescaleDB for state persistence. The Physical Crane Interface (a Python program) feeds real‑time measurements into the Logging Application, which stores them in the database. The Trajectory Generator Service creates optimal movement plans using a kinematics model; the Simulation Service can replay these plans; the Continuous Validation Service continuously compares logged measurements with simulated results, computes distance metrics, and raises alerts via the Grafana dashboard when thresholds are exceeded. All services are implemented in Python and run on virtual machines or containers, enabling modular deployment and resource management."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The exemplar is employed to illustrate continuous‑validation methods, fault‑detection techniques based on time‑series classification, and co‑evolution validation of the digital twin. Validation is achieved by comparing predictions of the kinematic model with measured behaviour of the physical crane and by applying the DarTwin notation for system evolution, constituting the quality‑assurance process for model fidelity."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "All digital‑twin services are deployed as Docker containers on a single host computer and orchestrated with Docker Compose. An Eclipse Mosquitto MQTT broker provides signaling between services, while the TimescaleDB database and Grafana dashboard are also containerized. Communication between services occurs over the local Docker network using MQTT for inter‑service messages and standard TCP/IP for database and dashboard access."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The twin runs on‑premise on a personal computer. Python containers are packaged in the pip‑installable module gantrylib, and the Database, MQTT Broker, and Dashboard are containerized with Docker. Deployment is performed via a provided Docker‑Compose file that starts and stops all containers on the host, offering a reproducible, single‑machine deployment with open‑source components."
]

